  "question": "Carlos is planting a lemon tree. The tree will cost $90 to plant. Each year it will grow 7 lemons, which he can sell for $1.5 each. It costs $3 a year to water and feed the tree. How many years will it take before he starts earning money on the lemon tree?",
  "prompt": "Carlos is planting a lemon tree. The tree will cost $90 to plant. Each year it will grow 7 lemons, which he can sell for $1.5 each. It costs $3 a year to water and feed the tree. How many years will it take before he starts earning money on the lemon tree?\n\nShow your work briefly and put the final answer in \\boxed{}.",
  "gold_answer": "13",
  "generated_text": "To determine how many years it takes to start earning money, we need to compare the cost of planting the tree with the revenue generated by selling the lemons.\n\n**Step 1: Determine the initial investment.**\nThe problem states that the tree costs **$90** to plant. This is the initial cost, so it cannot be covered until lemons are harvested.\n\n**Step 2: Determine the revenue per year.**\nEach year, the tree grows 7 lemons.\nSelling price per lemon = $1.5.\nTotal revenue per year = $7 \\text{ lemons} \\times \\$1.5/\\text{lemon} = \\$10.50$.\n\n**Step 3: Determine the cost per year.**\nThe problem states it costs **$3** a year to water and feed the tree.\n\n**Step 4: Calculate the net profit per year.**\nNet profit = Revenue per year - Cost per year\nNet profit = $\\$10.50 - \\$3.00 = \\$7.50$.\n\n**Step 5: Calculate the number of years to cover the initial investment.**\nTo start earning money, the cumulative profit must equal or exceed the initial planting cost of $90.\nNumber of years = $\\frac{\\text{Initial Cost}}{\\text{Net Profit per Year}}$\nNumber of years = $\\frac{90}{7.50}$\n\nLet's perform the division:\n$90 \\div 7.5 = 900 \\div 75$\nBoth are divisible by 25:\n$900 \\div 25 = 36$\n$75 \\div 25 = 3$\n$36 \\div 3 = 12$\n\nAlternatively:\n",
